#: src/rust-next/pin.md:1
msgid "Pinning"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-next/pin.md:3
msgid ""
"![Minimum Rust version: 1.33](https://img.shields.io/badge/"
"Minimum%20Rust%20Version-1.33-brightgreen.svg)"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-next/pin.md:5
msgid "Rust 1.33 introduced a new concept, implemented as two types:"
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-next/pin.md:7
msgid ""
"[`Pin<P>`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/pin/struct.Pin.html), a wrapper "
"around a kind of pointer which makes that pointer \"pin\" its value in "
"place, preventing the value referenced by that pointer from being moved."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-next/pin.md:10
msgid ""
"[`Unpin`](https://doc.rust-lang.org/std/marker/trait.Unpin.html), types that "
"are safe to be moved, even if they're pinned."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-next/pin.md:13
msgid ""
"Most users will not interact with pinning directly, and so we won't explain "
"more here. For the details, see the [documentation for `std::pin`](https://"
"doc.rust-lang.org/std/pin/index.html)."
msgstr ""

#: src/rust-next/pin.md:17
msgid ""
"What _is_ useful to know about pinning is that it's a pre-requisite for "
"`async`/`await`. Folks who write async libraries may need to learn about "
"pinning, but folks using them generally shouldn't need to interact with this "
"feature at all."
msgstr ""
